<review>If you want your beloved pet die due to negligence and at the same time receive a CPR charge of $1030 that the medical staff agreed not to do and did not do, then bring your pet here. Dr. Leah Kramer recommend  against it because she found a large tumor in his throat that completely blocked his airway. We followed their recommendation and painfully told them not to perform the CPR. We asked if we could be with him during his last moments. They said we could not due to Covid protocols. Two minutes later, we were informed of his passing.
We spent 15 minutes with our boy in the private room then did the financial check out. After paying, we found out the charge was close to $1,500 which included the CPR charge of $1,030. My wife asked the receptionist to refund the CPR charge since it was not performed. She said she could not do it because the payment was being processed by a third party. She told us to wait for a day or two for the processing to complete then would refund the $1,030 to us. My wife asked for the treating doctor's name and was told her name was Leah Kramer. At that time Dr. Kramer passed by and told my wife: "I will make sure the refund will be processed."

What happened was witnessed by many. We know through disputes or small-claim legal process that we will get our refund back. My only question is: Why does AIMSS operate like this?
My advice to all pet owners and lovers out there is to do your research ahead of time to look for an emergency facility other than AIMSS for your beloved pets. It's hard to find one during this pandemic time. This AIMSS hospital knows that and they intend to open their facility to take advantage of your animal-love situation.

< text>
I discovered at 1AM that my hatchling ball python had managed to dislodge athletic tape in his enclosure that I was using to hold the thermostat probe in place (dumb move on my part using tape; I took all of it out immediately and now use aquarium-safe silicone sealant). He got it stuck to his scales, and it wouldn't come off even with a warm bath. I was scared it might prevent him from excreting, and decided to see a vet.

To my knowledge, AIMSS doesn't normally see reptiles but when I called the receptionist was very polite and professional, and they offered to see him anyways. They were very prompt, got it off quickly, and didn't overcharge me at all.

I can't speak for anyone else's experience, but if mine is a standard example then I would fully expect the negative reviews here have more to do with the pet owners than AIMSS. This is a solid, professional clinic of highly trained experts.

I fully endorse AIMSS and would happily go back if needed!<//text>

<text>I've used this emergency clinic (and some of their specialty services) several times over the years always with good results and professional, competent service, but I had a really bad experience here yesterday. I don't want to single out any one person as it seems more like an institutional problem.

I didn't hear from the doctor for over an hour, and then only to tell me that he needed xrays and blood work. Of course he did, he was very sick! Then another 2 hour wait to tell me the xrays and blood work were done and was told the xray showed a tumor and maybe heart failure but the doctor wanted an outside radiologist to make a more expert interpretation and this was being asked for STAT. Another 3 1/2 hour wait to be told that the radiologist says he has pneumonia, no tumor, no heart failure. By now he's been there for more than 7 hours. By the time they discharge him at 8 hours, he had not received any medications or any fluids, although the doctor says she gave him a bowl of water at some point.

When I expressed my unhappiness that he had not received any treatment and the STAT read on the xray took 3 1/2 hours, the doctor agreed to give him his first dose of ORAL antibiotics rather than having me give it to him at home. If he has such a severe pneumonia that it looks like a tumor on xray shouldn't he be getting IV antibiotics and fluids?

Every conversation I had with the doctor was pleasant and I felt she really cared about my dog and was trying her best to get him taken care of. So where was the problem? It seemed to me that the clinic was extremely understaffed, at least from what I could see of the front desk and the very few nurses or techs who were doing intake. We were there mid day (11am-7pm) on a Saturday, which I would think would be an important staffing period for the only emergency vet in the city. Also, when I got my dog home, he had to pee for a very long time, and was incredibly thirsty which made me think he hadn't been taken out or given much water during his 8 hours there. <text>I know that the reviews on AIMSS are all over the map because I looked them myself before taking my dog here for an eye infection, but my experience was ultimately just fine.

My dog developed an eye infection on a Sunday so most vets were closed. On Monday morning I started calling around, but because of COVID vets are impacted and either didn't have any availability same-day or weren't taking new patients. I learned that AIMSS is essentially an Urgent Care type of place and that I could get him in to see a doctor same-day with the knowledge that that type of service would cost $120. My dog's eye infection was bad enough by that Monday morning to warrant seeing a doctor that day and I thought the cost was reasonable.

When I arrived I did find it difficult to see the place (it's behind a big tree) and also difficult to see their parking lot, which is immediately adjacent to their building - between them and the auto body shop next door. I will say that the staff they have answering general phone calls are pretty blunt and uncaring. When I didn't see the parking lot and parked just beyond the auto body shop I called and they asked me to park in the parking lot. When I parked in the parking lot and called they asked me to take my dog to the front door. All of that didn't generate a lot of confidence, but at that point I was there and took the risk.

From then on I'd say that I was happy with the service I received. I got a phone call within 40 minutes of the handover asking a few more questions about my dog's symptoms before the doctor saw him. A reasonable amount of time later I got a call from the doctor herself with a diagnosis. Then a call from a tech with discharge instructions. They handed my dog back to me within 2 hours of me dropping him off, maybe even 1.5 hours. The techs and the doctor were much nicer on the phone and explained everything thoroughly.

Overall I'm happy with the experience. If I were to ask them to make one change it would be to train their general office staff (who answer general phone calls) on being a bit warmer and empathetic with the customers and potential customers who call in.<//text>< Pics>

I had a hard time understanding whether these people wanted to take care of my dog or wanted to extract as much cash from me as possible.

If I could write a script or how to take advantage of somebody to get the most money out of someone in an emergency situation, the doc here followed it to the letter.

My dog is alive, but did not receive treatment beyond the expensive tests they were running for nearly five hours after getting here while having a heart rate of 250 beats per minute.

The staff has an alarming lack of empathy, and the communication is broken at best. Ambiguity with which this week and the oh so upfront palpable 'give me all your money' attitude is upsetting to say the least.

They took advantage of me in an emotionally vulnerable state. While I was waiting in my car to see what would happen I contacted a friend of mine who also had an unfortunate run in with this place.

Update: I brought my dog in for a follow-up appointment this morning to have an ultrasound. The nurse not only thought I was dropping off a cat, but she did not change the expression on her face once, hardly bent down, did not invite my dog inside, but just started dragging him by the neck to take him inside to give him the ultrasound. This behavior is completely deplorable. I immediately regret that I brought him back here instead of getting a lawyer to get some of my money back.

I give 2 stars because my dog is alive. The doctor seems to know what she is talking about, although her salesmanship is her stronger skill.</Review>

This was the only emergency pet hospital open in SF on Sunday evening when we needed to take my puppy that apparently ingested drugs off the streets of San Francisco to emergency. To say the least, we were extremely scared. He‚Äôs less than one years old miniature Pomeranian. After waiting 1.5 hrs, I called to check in as they said they would treat him right away. Each person I spoke to communicated a different thing to me that was not adding up - including the admin, nurse, and even the doctor. I asked simple questions like: when are you going to treat my dog it‚Äôs been 1.5 hrs already and I‚Äôve now been told it‚Äôll be another 1hr+ now, why is there such a lack of communication, what does ‚Äúhe‚Äôs stable‚Äù mean, when do you think you‚Äôll be able to treat him I‚Äôm very concerned that he‚Äôs not comfortable waiting for treatment there, etc. The nurse diminished my concern repeatedly by saying my dog was not a priority compared to the other cases and attempting to teach me about what triage means as if relevant to my concern. Then, she gave me an ultimatum that if I didn‚Äôt want to wait or wasn‚Äôt happy with the service I could take my dog elsewhere - as if I had a choice and this wasn‚Äôt an emergency situation. She said ‚Äúso what‚Äôll it be? You want us to treat your dog or not?‚Äù Again, still wasn‚Äôt clear on how or when they were going to treat my puppy. How does it help to provide general answers with no specific info or process to concerned dog owners that adore their pets and cannot speak for themselves?

This is late at night, of course during COVID so we also can‚Äôt be with our little one, and we are sitting in our car out front waiting this whole time. There is obvious frustration that will arise and again, there was a total miscommunication between staff. After a little over 2.5 hrs of waiting, the doctor then called saying they finally treated our dog and then proceeded to threatened me that if I wanted to come back to ever receive service there that I have to be respectful. I explained to her pretty calmly that I felt the nurse was being incredibly insensitive and wasn‚Äôt speaking to me respectfully and that honestly I hope not to come back again because this was an emergency situation where this was the only emergency open and all I wanted was to understand when and how my dog would be treated because I love my dog. Then, in our dogs discharge documents, the doctor who was apparently extremely busy and couldn‚Äôt treat my dog for 2.5+ hrs, had the time to write a very disrespectful and long note personally attacking me calling me a ‚Äútrantruming child.‚Äù FYI  ‚Äútrantruming‚Äù is not a word - it‚Äôs a misspelling, ‚ÄúDoctor.‚Äù And, thanks for obviously taking your stress out on your already stressed our clients who are paying a ridiculous premium to get emergency care for their innocent animals. It‚Äôs incredibly unprofessional to put a personal attack in the discharge documents for my dog which should outline how I care for him after treatment! < Review>
Took my older dog in very sick late at night, as they were the only one in the area not at capacity. They are more expensive than others (private practice). Unfortunately, they're horrible. The doctor told us what she thought was wrong and had him admitted for aspiration pneumonia and another issue. She explained what they needed to do and why. I agreed but asked they wait on the ultrasound. She agreed. She told us that we were going to be contacted between 8 and 10 the next morning by the doctor for an update and results of some blood work, then again around 6 in the evening and that we can call anytime, as many times as we want to, just to check on him. No problem. Sounds great. Signed paperwork virtually. Since we weren't allowed inside because of COVID-19. I'm all for their protective procedures. The other lady who takes care of the front desk stuff was supposed to send me paperwork to sign without the ultrasound on it. Nothing. Then came morning.

8am. No call. 10am. No call. I call to check and they say the doctors have a couple of critical patients and haven't made rounds on current patients yet. Ok. Call at 12. Get attitude and the same excuse. Call at 2. Get more attitude and the same excuse. Call at 3:30 and get even more attitude and the same excuse. Now I'm wondering if they're even treating him and I start questioning them about if they're even treating him and what the hell is going on. I talk to the nurse and told her what I was told by the night doctor before leaving. Then she starts to argue with me because she says that's not how they do things and that no news is good news and I just have to trust them. I've never even been there before so how can I when I was told one thing and they can't even have a doctor call me after him being there for 14 hours with no communication. Then I was told they're not sure why she said that but that's not how they work. I told her that they need to 'school' the overnight doctor about the procedure. She said she can't do that but she can teach or advise her. I told her its the same thing, she said its not. ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è The last straw of excuses was when she said something and I told her 'so what. Is this because he isn't a regular patient there and the others are?' She got quiet for a moment and then said 'let me see if I can get the doctor on the phone.' Then the doctor came on, gave me some information, answered my questions, and then proceeded to tell me that the ultrasound I asked them to hold off on wouldn't have given them any information about his condition because it doesn't tell you what they needed to know. I'm thinking ok, so you tried to get me to agree to a $600 ultrasound that would have done me no good to find out anything related to my dogs condition.  I had enough. The doc agreed to see if he will eat and, if so. He will go home and see his primary for follow up xrays and that she would send the records to his regular vet immediately. I picked him up that evening and called his vet the next day. Of course, no one sent the records. My vets office had to call over to ask for them. I was supposed to receive a call the next morning to talk about a hefty refund of what I was charged for but they didn't do (he was ok to come home earlier than they said he would be). Never got a call from anyone. I'm going to check my credit card statement to make sure that they issued the promised refund. If they did, cool. If they didn't, they'll be receiving another call from me, except I won't be so patient this time.

Needless to say, I will never take my dogs there again, nor will I recommend them to anyone. Be wary of this veterinary practice.</Review>

I was right and they were right, they found a serious injury in my dog‚Äôs spine. They kept me posted on each test while I waited anxiously at home. My dog is now on bed rest with medications to keep him comfortable and heal him.

I arrived at AIMS a few hours after having taken my pet to a different emergency service(SPCA on Fillmore). The previous hospital had been dismissive of my dog‚Äôs pain. They explained away and dismissed my reasoning of something being seriously wrong with my dog. The contrast in the hospitals is shocking to me.

Competent doctors, nurses and staff who listen, are kind and put the animals health first. They are also responsive and answer questions over the phone.

AIMS, thank you for taking care of my best friend.<//Text>

<review>Cruel. Cold. Incompetent.

All of these added up to the absolute worst, most painful experience of my life, this May of 2020.

Cruel:

I was referred to AIMMS by my regular vet, SF SPCA (because of them referring me here I will no longer use them either). My dog was in pulmonary distress, and AIMMS admitted her. For two days she stayed there, and being in the middle of the pandemic I couldn‚Äôt even visit her (this I understood, it just made everything worse).

Two days later she was sent home, with four different medications to be administered at different times every day. Upon my arrival home I was greeted with the paid receipt in my email: Over $8,000. Yes. EIGHT THOUSAND DOLLARS. As long as she was feeling better, I didn‚Äôt care about the money. She is my soulmate, and you cannot put a price on that. I was determined to faithfully administer her medicine, making sure the remainder of her beautiful life was safe and comfortable.

Unfortunately, back at home it was abundantly clear that my little girl was still in distress. She was shaking, lethargic and unable to hold her bladder. I called AIMMS again and they advised me to bring her back immediately.

After waiting, forever it seemed, outside to receive the vet‚Äôs phone call from just inside the office, I was told there were a few things they could do, including adding more medications, running a urinalysis, etc. By then I HAD to ask if there was really any point to this. The vet hemmed, hawed and provided no real helpful information.

Without going into the painful details, after numerous calls to family and friends, I had to make the impossible decision to say goodbye, and put my best little friend to sleep. I have never cried more, and I do to this day. What made it worse is knowing that she had been put through hell for the last two days. WHY did they do this when it was clear she was not going to make it? Hence, DOWNRIGHT CRUEL.

Cold:

I was allowed in for the euthanasia procedure. It was in a cold room, with an equally cold female vet. I was crying so hard I could barely stand, holding my little girl and saying goodbye. When it was time, I was given no explanation of what to expect, other than ‚Äúshe‚Äôs going to get sleepy.‚Äù She DIDN‚ÄôT get sleepy. Instead, she simply collapsed on the cold steel table, at which point the vet simply said, ‚ÄúShe‚Äôs gone.‚Äù She then began a matter-of-fact discussion with the friend I had called to be with me on how much more ‚Äúhumane‚Äù we are to our pets than to each other. I had to scream, ‚ÄúSHUT UP, PLEASE!!!‚Äù while I held on to my girl's lifeless body, erupting in convulsive tears. My girl was indeed gone. I was inconsolable. The vet was just COLD.

Incompetent:

I was told to call the following week to tell them what was to be inscribed on my girl‚Äôs urn after her cremation. I called, told them, and had them read it back to me to make sure I got it right. Two weeks later, I retrieved the urn. I fell apart all over again. After many moments, crying in the car with my friend who brought me, I opened the cardboard box to see the actual wooden urn, only to realize they had MISSPELLED the inscription! Talk about insult to injury. Talk about shear INCOMPETENCE.

And, in fact, the close friend who brought me to pick up her remains admitted to me later that he had an equally horrible experience there resulting in his cat being put to sleep. He didn‚Äôt tell me at the time because he knew how devastated I was.

In closing, I can only say beware. Just drive by this place and you‚Äôll witness what a dump it is from the exterior. You can be assured that the interior is just as bad. The staff is neither caring nor compassionate. My little pup died a horrible death at the hands of these people, and she should not have had to go through the hell they put her through.

And, to add even more pain, upon arriving back home, without my little girl, there was yet another paid receipt awaiting me. I couldn‚Äôt even look at it. I just trashed it.

This veterinarian DOES NOT deserve your business. PLEASE AVOID!< /review>< user_id>

<name>Emily Risk</name>< review>
I am grateful for the excellent service my sweet kitty boy has received over the years we have been going to AIMSS. He was a real tough guy who made the most out of his nine lives.  I feel the care he received was always appropriate and the providers were consistently kind, super knowledgeable honest and clear (even in the middle of the night). I took him to a primary veterinarian until he was diagnosed with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy after which I only felt comfortable taking him to AIMSS.
One night after getting a clot in his paw  (super painful) I took him in and Dr Williamson diagnosed him in about 2 seconds and gave me the facts about blood clots in cats. He was a lucky one and she saved his life again. The first save was when I brought him in because he was breathing with his mouth open, not normal for cats. I feel la debt of gratitude as we got more quality time with our sweet boy.
Is it expensive? Yes, but that is what emergency care cost. I never felt any procedure was unnecessary or that I was not informed about the cost or that I had no choice.  Dr Black worked getting me set up with an outside pharmacy, and Dr Williamson suggested GoodRx to obtain better prices on medications; both excellent recommendations that made a significant difference in medication expenses.
Do you have to wait? Sometimes...just like the ER for humans. But I found that they do a great job of triaging the animals. So if you have to wait, be patient it just means they are working on saving a life.  In the non emergency times when I had to wait for Cookie to be seen, I was happy to wait because Cookie could wait, he was alive and living a good life, a life he would not be living if it was not for the amazingly qualified and compassionate people at AIMSS. As far as how things went at the end of Cookies stay on the planet... well, true to form the folks at AIMSS handled me, my family and the sweetest cat in the world with the utmost care. That is never easy for anyone. So,  if your furry friend needs emergency care don't hesitate, go to AIMSS.<//review>

On the rare moments you have had the time to speak with me, you‚Äôve explained the boom of business you‚Äôve been experiencing due to the other emergency vets in the Bay Area cutting their hours and how overwhelming it has been for your clinic. This is the after care I am referring too. When an animal is admitted to the veterinary hospital for an emergency their care does not stop at discharge.
It is unfortunate that your clinic is experiencing growing pains. It is unfortunate that your clients are not receiving the aftercare that they need and deserve. <rate>2< /rate><name>Cindy Cobb</name><Resp>None< /Resp>< Text>
Incredibly Expensive
My 15 year old dog had a diabetic episode while we were out of town. Our dog sitter brought her to AIM and told them she was diabetic and that she had a seizure.
I spoke by phone to the vet on duty and explained that this had happened before and please do what you can but do not perform any unnecessary procedures such as x-rays.
She was there approximately 8 hours before she had to be euthanized.
The bill was over $4,000, including charges for x-rays. I paid the bill but a few days later requested a detailed explanation of the charges. I sent two follow-up requests but still have not received a response.
My dog had a previous diabetic emergency and we took her to VCA where she had to stay for 48 hours. The bill was approximately the same as it was for 8 hours at AIM. So, beware. If you have time to choose an emergency vet, AIM is outrageously expensive!</Text>

< Text>
Avoid at all cost. The staff at AIMSS is terrible at what they do and even worse at communication. Their catch line is "We're concerned about your pets health we should run some more tests just to be safe."

I had to admit my dog to AIMSS after hours on a Sunday and didn't know what to do but say OK to every procedure. The catheter they had inside my dog slipped out the second day, and they charged me for an x-ray because the vet couldn't remember how long the catheter was and wanted to make sure nothing was left inside.

That being said I had the stitches removed earlier this week and there was one poking out of my dog's skin, and it looked like it swelling up, so I called them last night to ask them if the sutures are dissolvable or not. The guy who picked up the phone told me that he can't help me right now because he has other CLIENTS that need help.---- Let me get one thing straight my pet is not your client my pet is a patient! He might not need attention ASAP, but regardless of the situation, there is a proper way to communicate with worried pet owners.
I asked him if he could give me a time frame so I could give him a callback and he told me he doesn't know when the nurse or the doctor will be free. I politely thanked him and gave him a call 2 hours later asking the same question which is to check his surgery report and tell me if the stitches are dissolvable or not. This time he decided to hang up on me. I'm not going to bother you guys by explaining the # of times I had to call them. Long story short 4.5 hrs later I was able to get the surgery report emailed so that I could go to another Vet and find out if my dog's stitches are dissolvable or not.

They don't care about your pet. They will take advantage of you in your most vulnerable state, misguide you and stop communicating if you're not reaching for a credit card. Their practices are unethical and should really be fined for taking advantage of people.<//Text>

My family and I made a reservation to get an SUV big enough to accommodate 7 of us. We asked to get a car that could cross the border, as we are going on a small vaca to Ensenada. We booked a suburban and paid for Mexican liability insurance and other fees because we were obviously going to Mexico. Once I arrived to pick up the car at their Long Beach airport location the manager said I couldn't take this vehicle across the border. Since we had booked directly with their 800 line I asked him to call his customer service and confirm our reservation. He refused to call stating he knew his policies. I used my cell phone to call their customer service line and was again assured we were ok to rent and take the car to Baja. The Long Beach manager still refused to speak with their own customer service dept, even while I had them on speaker!!! To make an already long story short, there wasn't one person at Avis in Long Beach that would help me or take a second to double check their policies with their corporate office. It would've been nice of them to take an ounce of interest and attempt to provide good customer service. I was at this place for about 2 hours going back and forth with the manager, Brian Fish and their customer service line. RUDE RUDE RUDE!!!

BTW... ended up getting a minivan at half the price of Avis = )

< Review>
It was so busy last night and I had a big order that kept me waiting even longer for my food ( 50 piece and 2 sides). All that waiting and they forgot my side orders! Too late to call , I called this morning and to my surprise Alex took care of my missing side orders. I am amazed at how he handled my situation- because i also understand i have no "actual" proof that this, but who calls for a missing $8 for 10 wings who really got them?  Anyways, I'm glad the manger handled the situation at hand the way he did and for this I will remain a wing stop customer. Thank you for making this right Alex,, I was sadly prepared to be ripped off - but you made sure that was not the case. I hope you ended up having a better day than me!< /Review>

<review>I'll admit I was a little skeptical about wait times due to some of the reviews, especially since my family was looking for a quick pit stop off I80. I made an online order about 15 minutes away on a Thursday night, and the website said the order would take 18-23 minutes. After showing up to the restaurant, where 3 groups were already eating, we quickly paid, and the cashier said it would be just a few minutes. We went to the bathroom, got our drinks, and got our food a little over 5 minutes after arriving. Very reasonable! The cashier also offered us some extra sauce. The wings were hot and delicious! <Rate>1< /Rate>< text>
Funny thing is I go here more often than I'd like to admit.

Recently my Wife ordered online and as usual we received a message saying the food was ready.  Once I arrived at the Wing Stop as usual the food wasn't really ready.

Typically they just tell me that it'll be another 10 minutes and I pay but this time it wasn't just another 10 minutes.  Instead, I found myself waiting for about an hour.

I'm a patient man and I was already out to pick up the food so I didn't really feel like heading somewhere else at 10 at night.

After seeing me wait for some time a guy, one of the employees, comes up to me and asks if I'm waiting on something and I replied with the name on the order.  After reviewing what happened he went back and realized my order wasn't made or close to being made yet.

After figuring out that my order wasn't ready he apologized more than he ever needed to and asked me if there was anything else I'd like.  I asked for maybe another thing of bleu cheese and that was it.  He happily obliged and after about 15 additional minutes all was supposedly right with the world.

Finally I get home and begin unpacking the all the wings n such and once I open the package containing my order I realized they forgot to put the original hot sauce on the wings.

Regardless, I still ate the wings as I was hungry and didn't feel like addressing the problem immediately.

Not sure what's going on lately but it's just been one fumbled order after the other. Usually missing veggie sticks or fries but  I think I'm simply going to just hold off on Wing Stop until either the staff becomes properly trained, quit or fired.  I hate to say it that way but that's just the way it is.

Overall!!!

Usually love the wings amongst everything else on the menu.

The staff could use a chin up because they're typically borderline rude but I look past it.

The staff could use some development with their abilities to multitask, take food orders and overall customer service.  Oh and double check their finished orders for accuracy.

Other than that, I probably won't be dropping by any time relatively soon.  I'll give it a good 6 months or so to see if anything has changed.<//text>

<user>115445451236206595196<//user>< username>
Kate Burns< /username>
<time>1528388597330<//time>< Rating>
3</Rating>
< Review>
UPDATED: The owner of the Portola Frosty contacted me. She was very apologetic, and explained what had happened was while she was out of town, another person had bought supplies for the restaurant, and purchased a different product.

Because they were working with a different product than usual, they did not realize the cook time was to be so different.

They have since replaced their stock with the usual product and measures have been taken to ensure the purchase of the right product in the future.

She told me that she would be going over some more training with the employees, to make sure they respond appropriately to situations in the future.

She also offered to buy My partner and I dinner at the Log Cabin when they open.

The environmental health department did do an inspection and helped put me in touch with the owner.
The Frosty passed the inspection fine, and the environmental health department assured me they believe the Portola Frosty is not in the habit of serving raw food to people, that this was a one time oversight. (After discovering the source of the issue, I agree)

I feel the environmental health department and the owner did respond appropriately to the situation overall, and hope the kiddo will learn to have better pride in her customer service skills in the future.

Original post:

My first choice was not to put this on social media, but my lack of ability to get ahold of anyone to talk to has changed my mind about writing this review.

I should not have to work so hard to talk to someone who will handle this with an appropriate amount of care.

This weekend the Portola Frosty served me RAW CHICKEN, very raw. It was burned on the outside and raw like sushi on the inside.

I ordered to go, and noticed when I got home. I really just wanted to call them and let them know. However, they would not answer the phone (they would pick it up and then hang up immediately), and there was no answering machine picking up for them, so I decided to go back to the Frosty and tell them. Being concerned they may serve others undercooked food also.

When I approached the window with my bag of raw chicken, the kiddo that came to help me, only said ‚ÄúI am sorry, I understand...‚Äù And kept repeating ‚ÄúI understand‚Äù whenever I finished a sentence. She was not rude to me, and I was not rude to her.

If I was complaining about getting tomatoes when we didn‚Äôt order them or the wrong flavor of ice cream, I could understand her shutting me down rather than addressing my complaint (still bad customer service but she‚Äôs a kid, hopefully she will learn better eventually).

RAW CHICKEN is something that should get much more of a response than ‚ÄúI understand‚Äù. It is a hazard, and is potentially very dangerous.

She did not attempt to take my name, she did not promise me that it would never happen again, she did not offer to get her supervisor, or look at the chicken, she didn‚Äôt even offer me a refund.

Her lack of concern about the situation leaves me to believe that this will not be addressed, leaving potential for this to happen to others.

Please use caution when consuming food from this establishment, they do not take the best care with safe food handling, and their customer service lacking genuine concern for a minimum quality of product control.

#safefoodhandling #rawchicken #PortolaFrosty< /Review>

< Text>
Delicious pizza and suds! We beat the Sunday crowd by getting there at 5pm. It was busy by 6pm, but the food came out quick enough for us, but appetizers helped. There's a food only line on the right. Food and brew line to the left. Ask for samples of their brews.
Pizza was nice and doughy, but not thick like pan pizza, not too thin either. Loads of toppings!!!
The Carlsbad was outstanding... hope you like artichoke, pesto and fetaüòâ. BBQ cheeseburger had meatballs, not ground beef, I liked it more than I thought I would. I was expecting weird, but the meatballs made it seem more traditional.
Wings were baked, not bready. (The way i like it)
We got the veggie basket as a side, it was ideal for a family of 4 or two really hungry people.
For you beer bodies, they offer cans, growlers, and 6 packs to go.
There's a small parking lot adjacent and there's a pay to park across the street. If you want free parking, plan on street parking and walking a block or two.< /Text>

Pizza Port has a very chilled, laid-back vibe. We were quickly able to find a long table that accommodated our group. Note, that the tables are shared, so don't be afraid to chat up your neighbor.

<Rating>5<//Rating><review>I have been a fan of Pizza Port for many years. They keep the menu simple with pizza, salad, breadsticks, mozzarella sticks, and buffalo chicken wings and craft beer and soda and iced tea. I love all their food and they have lunch specials, like two slices and a drink or a slice, salad, and a beverage (non-alcoholic), and a couple other options. You can substitute a beer for an additional charge. They have the proper social distancing protocols on keeping your mask on when you are not seated at your table. You have to ask for napkins, utensils, parmesan cheese, or red pepper flakes.
The service is friendly and helpful. I fully recommend this Pizza Port in Ocean Beach, San Diego.
The toughest part about the Ocean Beach (OB) location is parking is scarce. Especially with the social distancing protocols in place, they took over the small 7 parking spot lot for outdoor dining.</review>< pics>

< review>
The beer buddies were super good with our beers. The price in the area can't be beat. If you get the $3 pints and a small pizza and some beer buddies it's a perfect meal for two. This is a favorite for us for date night! Love their chronic ale, easily my favorite.
----------------Editted a few months later-----------------

Edit: From five to three stars for super rude staff. First I tried to order slices and the bartender told me they weren't doing slices so I ordered two small pizzas. Before my order came up I watched several people order and pick up individual slices. So I then had two small pizzas and needed some to-go boxes. They normally have them sitting out to help yourself. They didn't have any available so I requested two boxes from the staff. The busser said to me "two boxes? Why do you need two boxes?" I explained I had two pizzas but he retorted with "uh huh." I allowed my -well over 21- boyfriend to sample my beer (he didn't want one but wanted to try it) and we had the busser inform us that he couldn't taste my drink without getting ID'ed by the bartender and then said if he saw it again he would "have to bounce us". Asking for an ID would have sufficed. He absolutely did not need to treat us like we were breaking the law. This is a brewery, you have to assume people will sample each other's drinks. It's not accepted to threaten to remove someone from the property over it without requesting an ID first.

I don't know if they were recently hit with a fine or what but this behavior is a little wild. This place has been a favorite of ours for years and the entire atmosphere totally flipped. I hope that this trend doesn't continue because it makes it extremely uncomfortable to dine and relax.< /review>

< userid>
114054506485824647528</userid>
< username>
Garrett Bredell< /username>
<date>1528700948747</date><rating>5< /rating>< review>
Pizza Port's OB location is a staple for every one of my visits to the area. It captures the spirit of the area so well - surf, beer, and a loose and casual feel. Just a little off the main drag, it's within easy reach for tired surfers and rubbernecks alike, and makes a fine choice when Hodad's is running a line around the corner.

First, I've really only had the pizza. And it's good, competing with NY Slice style pizza around San Diego (East Coasters might turn their nose up at the place, FWIW.) I've also sampled the kale salad which was inappropriately healthy given the settings. The real treat here is the beer, which is always diverse, experimental, affordable, and delicious. Pizza Port's social media game has been overshadowed by newer players, but the brewing and taste is still on point, and matches supremely with the pizza available.

Head in during the lunch special and get away with two slices and a beer for less than $10, then get back to the beach with your newly acquired gut. Or return to the main street and go shopping, if you can resist the temptation to nap.<//review>

<rating>2<//rating><Text>WARNING: Do NOT place orders via ChowNow.

I've been a regular at the OB and Solana Beach Pizza Port locations since childhood.

Yesterday, I placed an order online for pickup at the OB Pizza Port via ChowNow.  I arrived 15 minutes after receiving the notification that the food was ready.  Due to an error between the shop and ChowNow, my order was never received so I waited for it to be prepared (outside, standing on the curb due to COVID restrictions) after being quoted 15 minutes.  30 minutes later, I checked on the progress and was informed that I had been made the incorrect pizza and that they would finish the one I ordered in 10 minutes.  One hour after I initially arrived to pick up my food, I finally received what I ordered.

The women who served me were very kind and offered the incorrectly-made pizza for free in addition to what I ordered, which I really appreciated.  Unfortunately, because I had to wait an hour to receive my order, my girlfriend missed a seminar she needed to attend.  Going forward, I unfortunately won't be providing my business to the OB location.< /Text><pictures>None</pictures>< Response>

< Text>
It was okay. I was disappointed because I took my kids here SPECIFICALLY to have some of their house-made root beer and when I ordered it, was told that the machine was broken. Oddly enough, that was the same story I got when I visited the Solana Beach location a couple of years ago. Regardless, if they're not going to offer an item, I think that the menu board should note that it's not available. Also, I ordered the lunch special and when I told the clerk what type of pizza I wanted, she replied that the only options were cheese, pepperoni, or the pizza of the day. The menu board says "any slice pizza" - again, if it's only certain types of pizza that are available with the special, then the menu should note that, not say "Any." I ordered the pizza of the day and it was yummy. It was hot and fresh, and the servings were large. The orders came out in a reasonable amount of time. If you're not a regular, it's a little unclear what you're supposed to do after you're finished eating - bus your own table? Leave it there? Some signage would help with that too. All in all, it was an ok experience. I wouldn't drive out of my way to go there again (like I did this time) and circle the block again & again looking for parking, but if I was already in the area, I'd eat there.<//Text>

<review>Fantastic, absolutely fantastic! So many delicious pizza options and a beer menu that goes on for days, what more could you ask for?

Went here for the first time for dinner with a group of co-workers. Ordered the Pizza Lahaina, Pizza Laguna, and Pizza San Clemente (love the pizzas named after California beaches). Each pizza was more scrumptious than the next! I never would have believed that a pizza with black bean sauce as its base could be so good but it was a revelation. My favorite was the Lahaina, but I'm one of those people who likes pineapple on a pizza with Canadian bacon.

Great, laid-back atmosphere at this place. The next time I'm in San Diego, Pizza Port will be on the short-list of places to go!< /review>< Pictures>

< Review>
Great for a crowd. Went for a birthday party with a group of six. We ordered individually and ordered too much food. Medium pies are quite large. I love their "wings" night on thursday's!  At 49 cents each it's a good deal, but it's only for "Dine In"  I would go early because it gets very busy and very crowded.  They are a very popular spot! <response>None</response><name>Brian Ferdman< /name>< Text>
The beer is phenomenal, both their own brews and the high quality offerings on the guest taps. The pizza is probably great...for San Diego. However, if you're from the Northeast, you won't be very impressed by the chewy, doughy, carb-bomb crust. Of course, if you need something to soak up the delicious beer, the pizza or the pizza bites are a good call. But again, this place is all about the beer. That's why you want to come here.< /Text>

Loud, enjoyable bar/pizza restaurant. They have a large, visible brewery. The pizza is delicious and the place is perfect for football with TVs all around the restaurant. They also have a miniature arcade for the kids. Unfortunately, there is often little parking.

<UserId.>108766632033484052865< /UserId.><name>Jessica Nettles< /name><Date>1561488796531< /Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
Once again, while looking for pizza we found this place and just the pictures of the food alone brought us into Pizza Port on a Saturday afternoon.  We came with our 3 children, and while I wouldn't necessarily call it a "family restaurant" I was comfortable with my two youngest being there because it's a loud, upbeat place where their noise levels would bother no one.
It took a few minutes to decide what we wanted, but we had an order of buffalo wings, which were dry rub and not super saucy, so they were good.  My littlest two each had slices of their favorite pizzas and the hubby and I each got a small, he had the San Clemente, and I the margherita pizza.  The individual slices were insane, they were bigger than the plates they were on.  The San Clemente has a black bean sauce, and it had this unique flavor that made me think I was eating somewhere between a taco and a pizza...it was quite good.  Then of course there was the Margherita pizza.  Not the best one I have ever had, but it was good and I would eat it again.   Truth be told though, I tasted the San Clemente first and it was so flavorful and yummy that maybe my tastebuds were a little screwy and the Margherita was just plain at that point.
We also enjoyed a Beer Float, something we'd discussed trying many many times, but had never actually come across.  We did at Pizza Port, and the options for beers in my float were amazing.  I went with a coffee porter and was pleasantly surprised.  Not gonna lie, I was skeptical, but I came out of this experience a fan.
This location is good for an afternoon slice and a cold beer or two.  Bringing the kids is totally fine, and going without them is totally fine too.
The atmosphere is laid back, the food is good, and the beer is cold.  What more could you ask for?< /review>

< Text>
It's hard to write anything bad about this place since it already has a winning combination of pizza and beer. Add a killer location (Ocean Beach) to the list, and you've got the recipe for a great afternoon or evening out.

If I were to say anything negative about the joint, is it's a bit crowded. Don't expect to come to Pizza Port and get a private table for two. All seating is community style, and the place is loud... so be in the mood to be social! And if you aren't, just have a pitcher of beer and you'll be adding to the noise level in no time :-)< /Text>

Really nice vibe here at PIzza Port. People are rough around the edges but overall pretty friendly. <Response>None</Response><user_id>105929644731397610584<//user_id>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
<Text>I give Pizza Port 5 stars for the beer and 4 stars for the food. However I have a lot of non-craft beer drinking friends that come here just for the food, so my standards might be high. To me the pizza is the perfect complement to their beer - doughy, cheesy and loaded with toppings. Their beers are very underrated compared to other breweries in San Diego, mostly because they make so many that aren't all world-class. But all of them are above average, priced fairly, and served fresh from the brewery in a casual family-friendly environment. Frequently Pizza Port creates some beers that really knock it out of the park (Santa's Little Helper, Mongo IPA, Bacon & Eggs Breakfast Coffee Porter, etc.) They have a generous amount of taps devoted to "guest brewery beers" including Russian River, Ballast Point, etc. Their homemade root beer is awesome, I recommend trying a float. Or try some of their "beer buddies" which is cooked pizza dough bites brushed with garlic butter.</Text>< Time>
1412382964574< /Time>
</record></dataset><record>

< review>
The pizza is really just a vehicle to put out an extensive beer selection, but these sturdy brews are best reserved for beer connoisseurs, and are for those who like heavy-duty suds.  Zagat's 25 food rating is suspect, with pizza that only gets the job done; mediocrity for the undemanding.  If you want to go where the locals go though, and don't mind a lot of enebreated togetherness with them, it might be worth a try.  Not for kids at night.< /review>

113897371292918169007<//user_id>
< username>
Ian - Fr0wnZ<//username>
< date>
1410202495834< /date>
<Rating>4</Rating>< text>
Came in with a group of friends for our last meal during our San Diego trip. Most of the group heard great things about Pizza Port, so it had to be a clear winner? Parking can be an issue with limited spots available, but luckily we found street parking about a block away.

The atmosphere of the restaurant looked fun and inviting. There were many flat screen TV's around the restaurant playing the football game. The seating reminded me of long park bench tables, big enough to fit large parties of 20 or 30. The craft beer bar is located on the left side of the restaurant while food is in the middle.

As far as food, Pizza Port offers premium gourmet pizzas. I originally wanted the Pizza SF but two friends had already ordered that, so I just randomly chose the featured month pizza, Teriyaki Chicken. It was just okay and I probably wouldn't get it again. The flavors didn't mesh well for me; carrots & broccoli inside a cheesy pizza. The pizza's are portioned generously, so if you're one person just go with the individual. There's also arcade games towards the back of the pizza restaurant. Pizza Port reminds me of an adult Shakey's. I will definitely come back but order the pizza I want regardless of who in the group gets it.</text>

< Text>
Don‚Äôt be fooled by the name, Pizza Port is a great pizza place as well, but even if they didn‚Äôt have pizza at all, they would be a pretty great bar and brewery. The outside patio section under some palm trees is awesome on nice days. The inside is huge with lots of long tables and great for big gatherings or small get togethers alike. The beer menu is huge as the Pizza Port brewing empire has several facilities. There are probably close to 3 dozen beers on tap across the range from blonde ales to porters. There are of course multiple hop forward IPAs that go great on a hot day. Even the malty wheat and ales are pretty delicious. The inside is a good place to catch sports as well with many TVs. The pizza isn‚Äôt bad either. This is your place to go to grab a pint after some time in the sun on the beach for sure.</Text>

Great selection of experimental Craft beers. Pizza is good too.<//review>
<gmap_id>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352<//gmap_id><user_name>Justin Dybedahl<//user_name>< userid>
102036098461639903448< /userid>

< user>
103485627635972293253< /user>
< review>
This is the quintessential surfer/craft beer hangout.  I think I literally saw Jeff Spicoli (if you're not old enough to know who that is, forget it).

On a serious note, the only thing that is not awesome about this place is the parking situation, but then again what can you expect in OB and thank the flying spaghetti monster that there are no soul sucking multi-story parking garages ruining the vibe that is OB.

I haven't been to the other Pizza Ports yet, but this one was fantastic albeit packed to the gills.  As you probably already know there is a plethora of home brewed craft beers, as well as plenty of guest taps.  Heavy on the D/I/PAs, in fact when I was there I think they had 7 IPAs and  3 or 4 DIPAs.  The beer line and the pizza line are separate and there are virtually no vegetarian pizza options, unless you roll your own (which you can if you want).

If I lived in OB (I'm not sure how this is possible anymore with real estate prices the way they are) I'd be there several times a week.< /review>

<Text>I can't particularly say I LOVE their pizza but it's ok.  Their atmosphere is great and their beer even better. They brew their own beer and dozens of types!  All SUPER SUPER awesome!  It's a place for craft beer aficionados!  Their staff is always happy to be there and happy to serve you and I very rarely can complain about them.  The pizza is ok, they have great specialty ingredients and the larger the pizza the better the crust I think.  Don't get a small if you don't like a lot of dough more like a hand tossed pan pizza.  The large is good and the lunch slices even better!  In fact they have the best lunch deal in town!  An amazing garden salad that me and my bf share and HUGE slices of pizza and soda for 5$ and if you want a beer its a 1$ more for regular beer and 2$ for stronger beers.  They always have a unique slice of the day accompanied with the choice also of pepperoni or cheese everyday and the slice with the salad is perfect!  I ate this almost daily when I worked across the street!  They are fast and the lunch is good and soooooo cheap!! They also have great salads!  The port salad is one of my favs!  It's all veggies and has so much in it that is unique you'll never miss the meat!  Roasted red peppers, blue cheese, spring mix, marinated portobellos and more!  It's to die for!!!< /Text>< Pics>

<Text>We came here to hang out with friends, and this was a perfect spot. Great food, great beer selections, and great company!

We came here on a Sunday night, a night before Memorial day. It's been awhile, and I completely forgot how crazy busy it is in these Ocean Beach streets. We got luckily how easily we found a table fit for 8 people.  The place is always packed and  loud, however people are quite polite and respectful.

We tried out the honey beers, Carlsbad pizza, cajun bites, garlic bites and chicken wings.  The honey beers were a treat for me. I'm not much of a beer drinker, but the Honey beer is something I would keep ordering. It's light, tart, and a hint of honey for the after taste.  The carlsbad pizza intrigued me --with the mix of artichoke hearts, feta cheese, alfredo sauce and peppers. The pizza was a tasty creation. The saltiness and sweetness flavors worked well with the ingredients. Though, the chicken wings didn't impress me much. It was average. The cajun & garlic bites were ok. They were made in a pizza bread, and then cut into pieces, cajun ---with jalapenos & garlic -- stating the obvious, and put into a basket to share.

Whenever I'm in Ocean Beach, I'd be back here for the assortment of beers and pizza selections!<//Text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
